      "content": "I'll try to keep the goblin analogies to a minimum. To address your question, when it comes to thread, a medium-weight to heavy thread (around 50-60 weight) is usually recommended for silk charmeuse. A high-quality, silk-specific thread or a fine cotton thread can help reduce puckering. As for stabilizer, a lightweight, fusible web like tear-away or cut-away stabilizer can help prevent puckering and distortion. You can also try using a silk-specific stabilizer or a layer of interfacing on the wrong side of the fabric.\n\nRegarding the feed dogs, if they're too aggressive, you can try adjusting the tension on your sewing machine or replacing them with a type that's designed for delicate fabrics. Some machines also have a \"free arm\" or \"lockstitch\" option that can help reduce tension on the feed dogs.",
